      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im studying for my security+ exam and im a bit stuck on some of the core concepts. can u explain what the principle of least privilege is? like how would it actually work in a normal office network?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The principle of least privilege is a security concept that ensures a user or system account has only the minimum level of access necessary to perform its assigned tasks. In a normal office network, this means a regular employee shouldn't have admin rights to the entire server farm, but rather just the specific file folders they need to manage.\n\nThink of it like a goblin in a forest: the goblin only gets to eat the berries it can reach. If the goblin tries to eat the giant oak, it gets stuck. Similarly, if a user tries to access data they shouldn't see, the system blocks them immediately.\n\nThe core idea is that every account gets a \"goblin-sized\" access card. The more specific the card, the less power the goblin has. If you grant a goblin the power to open any door, it can easily get lost in the woods. By restricting access to only the specific door needed for its job, you keep the goblin safe and ensure it doesn't wander off into dangerous areas.\n\nIn your security+ study, remember that this is about \"principle of least privilege\" (PoLP). It's not just about having fewer accounts; it's about making sure those accounts have the *",
